Finally, something worthy of posting. 

Early Christmas dinner at Boka.

The tasting menu consisted of;

Maine Uni

Honeynut Squash - yuzu kosho

Cured Hiramasa

Black truffle Tortelli - by far my favorite dish

Brown butter roasted scallop

Dry aged Rohan duck

Roasted venison

Vanila ice cream - coconut cream & grape

Black sesame ice cream - puffed grains & hazelnut

Overall, I really liked how they curated their menu. Black truffle tortelli was insanely good. Every dish was above average, but main dishes lacked a bit of impact, and desserts needed some touch, in my opinion. But overall, the ambiance was good, service, and drinks on point. Worthy of Michelin Star and James Beard award.

A perfect full tray of deliciousness! Ube mochi! ü§§

IATB: Wagyu Truffle Cheeseburger at Small Cheval in Chicago, IL üçî

You likely already know Small Cheval, @auchevaldiner's fast casual burger off-shoot. But did you know their location on Wells has been serving a special Wagyu Truffle Cheeseburger only on Tuesdays in December? 

Wagyu Truffle burgers seem to be the trend of the moment with everyone from local steakhouses to Shake Shack offering them on their menus over the past few months. I think the incremental taste of wagyu meat used for a burger is miniscule at best, but I still opt for it every once in awhile. Small Cheval is my girlfriend's favorite burger, so I've had a not so insignificant amount of their cheeseburgers over the past few years. This burger beats the normal Small Cheval cheeseburger out. It was good enough to make me forget I was eating outside in 30¬∞ weather in Chicago in December, which is no easy feat. It was good enough to make me type this post out in the cold while waiting for an L train just in case you happen to be in Chicago and stumble across this post while the Tuesday is still relatively young so that you can make the trip yourself. Past today, you've got one last chance to get this burger next Tuesday... aaaaand I can't feel my fingers anymore.
